          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="verdict">
        <h2>The Verdict: When to Choose Which</h2>
        <p>A critical takeaway for investors is that these three companies are not truly direct competitors; they operate in distinct, complementary layers within the same multi-trillion-dollar AI technology stack. Your investment choice ultimately depends on which part of the AI value chain you believe offers the best risk-adjusted returns going forward, and how you choose to structure your broader portfolio strategy.</p>

        <ul>
          <li><strong>Choose NVIDIA if:</strong> You want foundational, inescapable exposure to the entire AI industry. NVIDIA is the ultimate "picks and shovels" play—if the overall AI market grows, regardless of which specific software company "wins," NVIDIA sells the underlying chips. However, as an investor, you must be comfortable paying a significant premium valuation for their currently dominant, nearly monopolistic market position, and you must accept the inherent cyclicality of semiconductor hardware cycles.</li>
          <li><strong>Choose Palantir if:</strong> You believe the initial hardware build-out phase is beginning to peak, and the next massive wave of financial value will be captured by the software companies actually applying AI to solve complex, real-world enterprise and government problems. Palantir represents a targeted bet on AI successfully transitioning from hypothetical data center training runs into tangible corporate boardrooms and military command centers.</li>
          <li><strong>Watch CoreWeave if:</strong> You are an accredited institutional investor currently seeking high-growth private equity exposure, or if you are a retail investor preparing for what will likely be a highly anticipated public offering. If and when CoreWeave conducts an IPO, it will offer public markets the purest available play on specialized AI compute infrastructure, serving as a highly focused, high-beta alternative to simply buying shares in massive, diversified tech conglomerates like Microsoft or Amazon.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>For most diversified portfolios, holding a mix of the foundational hardware (NVIDIA) and the applied software layer (Palantir) provides comprehensive exposure to the ongoing AI paradigm shift.</p>
      </div>

      <section class="faq-section">
        <h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

        <details>
          <summary>Is CoreWeave a publicly traded stock?</summary>
          <p>As of early 2026, CoreWeave is privately held, though it has seen massive private valuations and backing from major players like NVIDIA. Investors looking for exposure typically invest in its partners or wait for a potential IPO.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>How does NVIDIA's business model differ from Palantir's?</summary>
          <p>NVIDIA is fundamentally a hardware and platform company, designing the GPUs and software ecosystem (CUDA) that power AI. Palantir is a pure software company, providing data integration and analytics platforms (Gotham, Foundry, AIP) for government and enterprise.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Why is CoreWeave considered an NVIDIA partner rather than a competitor?</summary>
          <p>CoreWeave is a specialized cloud service provider built specifically to offer scalable access to NVIDIA GPUs. They are one of NVIDIA's largest customers and partners, helping deploy NVIDIA's hardware to end-users rather than manufacturing competing chips.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Which of these three companies has the highest margin?</summary>
          <p>NVIDIA boasts exceptionally high gross margins (often exceeding 70-75%) due to its near-monopoly on high-end AI chips. Palantir also has strong software margins, while CoreWeave operates a capital-intensive cloud infrastructure model which typically yields lower gross margins than pure software or proprietary chip design.</p>
        </details>

        <details>
          <summary>Is Palantir a good stock for AI exposure?</summary>
          <p>Yes, Palantir is considered a strong play on applied AI. While NVIDIA provides the 'picks and shovels' (hardware), Palantir provides the software platforms (like AIP) that allow enterprises to actually deploy and use large language models securely on their proprietary data.</p>
        </details>
      </section>

    </section>
